sec.p:
Despite these advancements, several aspects of perovskite solar cells remain a challenge. For example, in many different fabrication approaches, mobile ions have proven to be a major limitation12–16. Mobile ions or ionic defects were shown to be the source of current density-voltage hysteresis and were linked to a reduced stability of devices12,14,17–20. Moreover, ionic defects that form states within the bandgap which act as recombination centers, can reduce the photovoltaic performance of the device21,22. Despite their importance, characterization of ionic defects and their properties in perovskite materials is incomplete. According to calculations and experimental reports, the most likely native point defects in methylammonium lead triiodide (MAPbI3) perovskites are charged vacancies, such as VI+\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
